{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657451/1923123001/0139.xml":{"full_text":"12\nDEPUTY MARSHALS\nBUSY DURING 1923\nTraveled 800,000 Miles Serving\nDistrict Courts\u2019 Papers, Says\nReview of Work.\nMANY MAINTAIN OWN CAES\n\nAllowed But One Token for Each\nTrip Here.\nDeputy United States Marshals dur\ning- 1923 traveled over 800,000 miles\n-In serving writs and processes issuing\nout of the District Supreme Court, the\nMunicipal. Juvenile and Police courts,\naccording to Edgar O. Snyder. United\nStates marshal, who reviewed the\nwork of his office. In an address be\nfore the Washington Salon and United\nArts Society at the Playhouse re\ncently. Rudolphe De Zapp, president\nof the society presided.\nMarshal Snyder explained that he\nhas fifty-two deputies distributed\namong the various tribunals. The\ndeputies are allowed one car token,\nthe marshal said, for each trip made\nin serving a legal paper and frequent\nly \u2018hey make several attempts to se\ncure personal ser\\fcc on defendants\nand others. The deputies often use\n\u201cflivvers\" which they own and main\ntain at their own expense.\nThe deputies servyl in 1923 a total\nof 41.321 writs from the District Su- j\nprenie Court and 39 409 from the Mu\nnicipal Court. The fees from the\nformer aggregated J 20.968.74 and\nfrom the latter, J 24,256.87.\nAmong the property seized by depu\nties under writs of attachments, is\nsued hy the District Supreme Court\nand Municipal Court, according to\nthe marshal, were 26 auotrnoblles.\n$325,900 worth of real estate, 15 up\nright pianos, 75 telegraph poles, 293\nbales of cotton, one motor boat, and\nhousehold and office furniture valued\nat about J 15.000. and other articles.\nThe marshal's office sold at public\nauction thirty automobiles, one mule\nand other articles seized by prohibi\ntion forces and destroyed 17,952 bot\ntles of 6 per cent beer.\nTribute to Justice*.\nMarshal Snyder paid a high tribute\nto the justices who presided over the\ncourts for the last 123 years. He\nsaid \"in the 123 years of the exist\nence of the courts In the District, the\nbench shows a. remarkable ability in\nthe several chief and associate jus\ntices who presided over our tribunals,\nfrom Cranch, the first justice, down\nto the present incumbent. Chief Jus\ntice McCoy. Their careers are marked\nby uniformity of ability, broadmind\nedness,. patience and humanity,\" he\nasserted.\nSpeaking about his own office.\n.Marshal Snyder said that since the\norganization of the local courts thiire\nhad been twenty-four marshals, one\nof whom was Gen. Janies McKibben\nTubbln. who, although appointed, did\nnot serve. He was chief marshal at\nthe inauguration of Thomas Jefferson\nas President and collector of the port\nof Georgetown.\nj gfe Wrights Furniture\nI (L&ways \"Right\" mtyaUty and Price,'\nI 905 Seventh Street Phone Main 167\nOverstuffed and Other living\n\u2019ll 'la\nRoom Suites Deeply Reduced!\nAverage Reductions, 25% to 33 l /s%\n\n\u25a0I\nSlB5 .3-piece Qverstuffecl $348 3-piece Overstuffed Living Room\n\u201cKroehler\u201d Bed-Davenport Suite lOQ Suite, covered in velour. Re- IQA CA\nreduced to duced t<3\n\n$195 3-piece Overstuffed $275 Overstuffed Suite, 3 pieces, CI Q S\nLiving Room Suite, covered in Cljft covered in tapestry combination.\nvelour\n$225 Northfield 3 piece Bed- $375 3-piece Bed-\nDavenport Suite, taoestrv cov- CIAC Davenport Suite, with mohair\nere( j cushion seats\ni 1 $235 Overstuffed \u201cKroehler\u2019\u2019 $550 Mohair Overstuffed\nliij Bed-Davenport Suits, covered ITC \u201cKroehler\u201d Bed-Davenport Suite\nin velourf., VltJO reduced to\nt:j\n46 Lamps Reduced!\nmm 25% to 50% Below Former Prices\nOne of a kind only. Artistic in design and in good\ncolor combinations. Lamps for every room in the house.\nAn opportunity to pick up a genuine bargain.\n12 Table Lamps, a* $9.9$ Twwf*\nW .11 Bridge Lamps, at $14.75 w trjST\nII 9 Junior Lamps, at $17.50\n14. Floor Lamps, at $22.50 w t7VSS5f*\nWhite House Visitor\nWILLIAM ALLEN WHITE,\nNoted editor, photographed yesterday\nafter a conference with President\nCoolldge.\nRetirement Law\nIn Civil Service\nTo Be Reviewed\nMatters of importance to the civil\nservice are to come before the Senate\ncivil service committee soon after\ntheir reassembling of Congresa, in\ncluding the controversy over reclassi\nfication and amendments to the civil\nservice retirement act.\nSenator Stanfield of Oregon, chair\nman of the committee, said yester\nday that joint hearings before 4 the\nSenate and House committees on the\nproposed amendments to the retire\nment act probably would begin Janu\nary 14. These amendments would in\ncrease the maximum annuity paid to\nretired employes from $720 to $1,200\nand would reduce the age of retire\nment.\nCIVIC CLUB\u2019S ELECTION.\nThe Federation of Civic Clubs yes\nterday met at the City Club and\nelected the following officers for the\nyear 1924: President, George A. Lewis\nof the Lions Club; vice president, Lee\nL. Harrell of the Optomist Club; sec\nretary-treasurer. W. O. Hiltabidie of\nthe Civltan Club.\nMAN, 74, DIES SUDDENLY.\nJohn Ricketts, seventy-four, room\ner at 329 Pennsylvania avenue nortK\nwest, died suddenly In his room\nyesterday. Dr. H. H. Hoffman, mem\nber of Emergency Hospital, reached\nthe patient about the time he died.\nR. A. Ricketts, civil engineer in the\nfederal service at Florence. Ala,, son\nof the deceased, was notified.\nTHE SUNDAY STAS, WASHINGTON, D. 0.. DECEMBER 30, 1923\u2014PART 1.\n\u201cBATTLE\u201d WILL TEST\nCANAL WAR FACILITY\nAmy, Navy and Marine Corps to\nTake Fart in Panama\nManeuvers.\nIMAGINARY ENEMY EQUAL\nOperations to Occur Between Jan\nuary 16 and 82.\nThe Atlantic and Pacific fleets, the\nexpeditionary force of marines from\nQuantlco, Va., and Army forces num\nbering 9,000, in participating In joint\nmaneuvers, the first of the kind ever\nattempted in and about the Panama\nCanal Zone next month, will attempt\nto determine the effectiveness of the\nPanama canal as a means of national\ndefense.\nThe maneuver plan is Jiased upon the\nassumption that strained relations\nexist between the United States and\nimaginary enemies, equal in resources,\nman-power and naval strength.\nThe Atlantic fleet will represent the\nblack fleet for the purpose of the\nmaneuvers, while the Pacific fleet and\nthe Panama Canal Department will re\nmain blue. The safety of the eana)\nduring the passage of the Pacific fleet\nwill depend upon the Regular Army gar\nrison in the Canal Zone.\nInstructions giving details of the\nsituation have been sent to Army and\nNavy commanders to be opened at noon\nJanuary 14. and the operations will\noccur between January 16 and 22.\nChief umpires will be Admiral Eberle,\nchief of of naval operations, and Maj.\nGen. Hines, acting chief of staff.\nThree major purposes are embodied\nIn the maneuvers: First, to ascertain\n\u2018-'the ability of the Army to keep the\nPanama canal open In war with the\nmeans both In personnel and material\nplaced at Us disposal for the purpose\";\nsecond, to obtain data as to the time\nrequired to effect concentration of the\nfleet in either ocean by means of the\ncanal; third, to test \u201cthe practicability\nof joint supervision of the Army and\nNavy forces in an operation which\nnecessitates the joint use of all our\ndefensive elements.\u201d\nSPENGLER POST ELECTS.\nFred A. Livingstone Is Chosen as\nCommander by Veterans.\nThe new administration of Henry C.\nSpengler Poet, American Legion, has\nbeen elected as follows: Fred A, Liv\ningstone. commander; W. Lawrence\nHazard, senior vice commander; James\nB. Jones, junior vice commander;\nDouglas A. White, finance officer; Ed\ngar H. Hale, quartermaster; Bari E.\nSmithson, sergeant-at-arms; Glenn C.\nDorsey, master-at-arms; Charles R-\nLuce, surgeon; Arthur L. Smith, chap\nlain; Charles W. Moore, color bearer:\nRoy N. Purdy, color bearer, and Ben\nL. Fuller, historian.\nThe January meeting of the poet will\nbe held at the National Guard Ar\nmory, 472 L street northwest, Thurs\nday, January 3, at which time the\nLadle*\u2019 Auxiliary of the post also will\nmeet. The auxiliary will provide enter\ntainment after the Installation of the\nforegoing officers.\n\u201cThe World As It Was I\nt in 1923\u201d\n\nThere will be published ex- J\nchisively in Washington\u2014in\nWIK gening plaf.\n\n\u2014tomorrow\u2014December 31st\u2014\n\ni( 4\nA comprehensive Review of the Year 1923 \u2014touching every\nphase of the political, industrial, commercial and financial\nactivities\u2014local, national and international.\n\nThis resume has been prepared by special writers assigned to those sub-\njects with which they are intimately familiar and of which they write from\nT personal knowledge\u2014drawing the interesting conclusions that have important\nr bearing upon the coming year.\nr \u2014one that has ex-\nercised a tremendous influence upon the world\u2019s progress. You\u2019ll enjoy read-\nT ing it to refresh your mind on what has happened you\u2019ll want to preserve it\nr for future reference. n\n\n4 i\n\u2014Some of the Topics Covered j\nIf Complete review of District of Columbia matters\ngovernmental and financial. The great growth of the\ncity furnishes an interesting chapter.\n\u25a0M\nr The influences of Politics on Business The Story of Wheat, Corn and Grain\nduring 1923 \u2014By David Lawrence. and the price fluctuations during the year\ni The Old World Business Outlook for \u201cBy George Sdmackel. J\nAn analysis of Your lnve*tments-By Shee P and Ho industries-By LC.\nGeorge T. Hughes. Gmndeland.\nM The New York Curb Market in 1923 The Cotton Market in America and\nM By William F. HeSernan. abroad\u2014By George D. Monlson.\ni The Financial World during 1923\u20148 y Business Outlook at the close of 1923 J\nStuart P. West.' ByJ.C\u00dfoyle.\n\n\n\nYou must read The Star\u2014Evening and Sunday\u2014regu- )f\nM larly\u2014if you want to keep abreast of the times in news and